Senate Resolution 112
By: Senators Parent of the 44th, Orrock of the 36th, Halpern of the 39th, Jackson of the 41st,
Harrell of the 40th and others
A RESOLUTION
1 Recognizing February 6, 2025, as Girl Scout Day at the state capitol and commending the
2 Girl Scouts as a national leader in providing the best leadership development experience in
3 the world to American girls; and for other purposes.
4 WHEREAS, more than a century ago, native Savannahian Juliette Gordon Low started the
5 movement known as the Girl Scouts; beginning with the first gathering of 18 girls in
6 Savannah on March 12, 1912, Juliette broke the conventions of the time by reaching across
7 class, cultural, and ethnic boundaries to ensure that all girls, including those with disabilities,
8 had a place to grow and develop their talents and leadership skills; and
9 WHEREAS, the life mission of Juliette Gordon Low was to build girls of courage,
10 confidence, and character; and
11 WHEREAS, the Girl Scout Leadership Experience encourages girls to develop a strong sense
12 of self, connect to their communities both locally and globally, and feel empowered to make
13 a difference in the world; and
