14 WHEREAS, Girl Scouts offers hands-on, girl-led, and girl-centered learning in STEM, the
15 outdoors, and entrepreneurship and provides abundant opportunities to help girls develop
16 invaluable life skills; and
17 WHEREAS, the Girl Scout Gold Award, the highest honor a Girl Scout can earn,
18 acknowledges each recipient's power and dedication to not only bettering herself but also to
19 making the world a better place for others; and
20 WHEREAS, more than 59 million American women are Girl Scout alumnae, and 2.6 million
21 girls and adult volunteers are active members; and
22 WHEREAS, today, there are 43,000 Girl Scout members in the State of Georgia in every
23 corner of the state; and
24 WHEREAS, the movement started by Juliette Gordon Low now reaches every corner of the
25 world with Girl Scouts living throughout the United States, its territories, and in more than
26 90 countries across the globe; and
27 WHEREAS, today, the Girl Scouts of Historic Georgia and Greater Atlanta Councils serve
28 approximately 43,000 Girl Scout members in the State of Georgia.
29 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE that the members of this body
30 recognize February 6, 2025, as Girl Scout Day at the state capitol and commend the Girl
31 Scouts as a national leader in developing girls of courage, confidence, and character.
